Problem Statement

This project focuses on solving an image classification problem using classical machine learning techniques instead of deep learning. The goal is to understand how traditional methods can be applied to visual data and compare their effectiveness to modern approaches like CNNs.

Approach

In this project, I used classical machine learning algorithms to classify images. Since traditional models cannot directly process raw images, the workflow included:

Converting images into numerical features
Applying feature extraction techniques (such as flattening pixel values or using descriptors)
Training a machine learning model (e.g., Logistic Regression, SVM, or KNN)
Evaluating the model on test data

This approach emphasizes feature engineering instead of automatic feature learning like in neural networks.

Results

The model was able to classify images with reasonable accuracy.
Performance was lower compared to CNN-based models due to limited feature extraction capability.
Accuracy depended heavily on the quality of feature engineering.

Key Findings

Classical machine learning can still work for image classification but is less powerful than deep learning.
Feature extraction plays a critical role in model performance.
Models like SVM or KNN can perform well on smaller datasets.
Deep learning reduces the need for manual feature engineering.

